people sit currently, benchmark that a little bit, look for areas of improvement. I conduct

00:06:14.720 --> 00:06:20.079
one-on-ones. I try to be on top of the day-to-day workload for them as well. I don't

00:06:20.079 --> 00:06:25.839
want them being overwhelmed. Gradual progression is probably the easiest route to take for most

00:06:25.839 --> 00:06:33.600
people. So daily one-on-one check-ins, check-ins for the project as well. A lot of

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:38.959
my calendar is filled with meetings, we'll say. I see there are a lot of questions coming in the

00:06:38.959 --> 00:06:44.720
chat around management too, and one was a follow-up to Sam's question. Zach, do you want to jump in?

00:06:46.959 --> 00:06:51.920
Yep, can do. So yeah, it was just, it seems like a lot of questions about this. Like,

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:58.000
of course, traditionally, as you progress in your career, you turn into a manager.

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:02.239
I was just wondering, do you miss the coding side of it? I looked into New

00:07:02.239 --> 00:07:08.640
Ellington, you were a data scientist for about a year before moving up. So I presume it's just

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:14.480
natural career progression, but you said you weren't very hands-on these days. I was wondering

00:07:14.480 --> 00:07:20.880
what you thought about that. Yeah, so there's opportunities, you know, not within your daily

00:07:20.880 --> 00:07:24.480
profession to still establish some professional development if you're looking to enhance your

00:07:24.480 --> 00:07:29.200
technical abilities. Part of being a manager as well as, you know, being experienced with,

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:33.359
or at least have a baseline understanding of some of the technology that's currently in

00:07:33.359 --> 00:07:37.679
development, right? So moving to more cloud platforms, I think I've been learning a little

00:07:37.679 --> 00:07:43.600
bit more about data engineering, upping my Linux skills as well on the side. So it doesn't, you

00:07:43.600 --> 00:07:48.320
know, fall off the table. You still want to make sure you're up to date with the latest technology,

00:07:48.320 --> 00:07:53.040
understanding how some of that works, going through some tutorials as well. So I don't

00:07:53.040 --> 00:07:56.720
think it really just completely falls off the table. It's just not part of your day-to-day

00:07:56.720 --> 00:08:02.160
life anymore, but there's always opportunity. The continued curiosity is a big thing that I

00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:10.239
don't think ever really leaves you. I like that, continued curiosity. I see, Andreas,

00:08:10.239 --> 00:08:15.679
you had a similar question. I think it was maybe answered in that, but do you have any follow-up

00:08:16.799 --> 00:08:22.239
questions? I think it was mostly answered, yeah. I was just wondering the mix of managing and

00:08:22.239 --> 00:08:30.000
actually still hands-on technical parts, and if you sort of have a deliberate way of doing this,

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:37.200
or is it just whatever happens, happens? Well, I think it's kind of where the company's at as well,

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:42.159
where I look to round out some of my skillsets. You know, if it is ML ops, understanding how

00:08:42.159 --> 00:08:46.479
pipeline development works, eventually data scientists get a firm understanding of,

00:08:46.479 --> 00:08:50.080
you know, statistics and, you know, that technical knowledge doesn't leave you

00:08:50.799 --> 00:08:55.280
too quickly, thankfully, but the programmatic side of things, helping out with code,

00:08:55.280 --> 00:08:59.039
there's always going to be somebody on the team that is going to be more proficient at you at

00:08:59.039 --> 00:09:06.159
coding, so I don't think part of my role day-to-day will entail being that expert anymore, I would say,

00:09:06.159 --> 00:09:11.280
but you still need to have a little bit of a firm base as to how things work on a high level.

00:09:13.919 --> 00:09:18.559
I love all these questions that are coming in immediately. Everybody's ready to go today.

