I think I started off doing some economics during my initial master's. I think that was in business

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:47.840
intelligence and analytics. See, at the time, analytics was still relatively new. I'm showing

00:09:47.840 --> 00:09:53.919
my age a little here, but, you know, you got some deep dive understanding of how AI would work,

00:09:54.880 --> 00:09:59.919
you know, understanding some Python implementation, but the continued development,

00:09:59.919 --> 00:10:04.400
I would say, for me is, I wanted to get more, I wanted to take a little bit of a step back,

00:10:04.400 --> 00:10:09.440
I would say, so statistics is pretty much a lot by hand. You might use SAS a little bit.

00:10:10.320 --> 00:10:15.840
R is very common as well for statistical programming, but the inferential side,

00:10:16.479 --> 00:10:19.200
you know, I was trying to understand things from a business perspective.

00:10:20.559 --> 00:10:24.640
I wanted to take a little bit of a step back, like, see what I can get from some of these

00:10:25.599 --> 00:10:31.599
assumptions, you know, tests that you perform. So I would say my progression is just

00:10:32.960 --> 00:10:37.520
hopping around a little bit, seeing what fits well, you know, trying to master a skill set

00:10:37.520 --> 00:10:43.039
at a given period, and continuously moving forward, I would say, is the biggest challenge.

00:10:43.440 --> 00:10:49.039
Where's the next step for you in your career as well? So it's kind of my progression.

00:10:51.039 --> 00:10:58.000
Thanks, Joe. There's a lot of great questions coming in in the chat too. And Libby, I see

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:02.960
you had a comment about the job landscape today. Would you want to jump in and ask that question?

00:11:04.400 --> 00:11:11.520
Sure. So I've been talking to lots of people on teams around, you know, kind of in our R space,

00:11:11.520 --> 00:11:16.479
where they're really hiring just seniors are not really looking for anybody who's junior because

00:11:16.479 --> 00:11:21.440
they don't have the seniors in place to grow juniors yet. And I've been curious if that's

00:11:21.440 --> 00:11:28.960
been a challenge that maybe you faced in your org. Yeah, I mean, it's definitely a pain point,

00:11:28.960 --> 00:11:35.679
I would say getting more senior people in there. But part of the progression aspect with larger

00:11:35.679 --> 00:11:40.479
firms is maybe these more senior people aren't given the opportunity to mentor more junior

