it's a bit tough learning how to code. I never was taught how to code, but it's going very well.

00:15:57.760 --> 00:16:02.159
I'm just a little curious, how do you have people to work on you who have maybe a lot of some skills,

00:16:02.159 --> 00:16:06.239
but zero coding skills, and how do you encourage them to kind of go on their own with that sort of

00:16:06.239 --> 00:16:10.640
thing, if you do that? I don't know if that's, if you have anybody like how I've described myself,

00:16:10.640 --> 00:16:14.960
and where I am right now. And if you have any comments, then it'd be nice to hear. I don't know

00:16:14.960 --> 00:16:20.400
if, yeah. Yeah, we definitely have people that are, you know, unfamiliar with some semblance of

00:16:20.400 --> 00:16:25.919
coding. I think at any point in your career, you've written a formula in Excel. So just learning to

00:16:25.919 --> 00:16:35.919
translate that into, you know, more usable scripts, I would say. So how I develop people, and enhancing

00:16:35.919 --> 00:16:40.640
their programmatic efficiency. Again, kind of pairing them with somebody else, but you know, I

00:16:40.640 --> 00:16:45.200
think it starts with identifying what their, what their determined career path is from their

00:16:45.200 --> 00:16:50.239
own perspective, right? So some people, they want to be more statistics oriented. They want to either

00:16:50.239 --> 00:16:55.440
be, you know, more ML engineering oriented, right? So you have to understand, like, where's the focal

00:16:55.440 --> 00:17:01.039
point for their career going forward? What's the pain point that they have right now? What's the

00:17:01.039 --> 00:17:07.199
quickest way to kind of upskill them in that sense? So the most recent case that I

00:17:07.199 --> 00:17:11.920
have is, we had somebody that really wanted to, you know, get into more of the architectural design

00:17:11.920 --> 00:17:18.079
space. So, you know, getting them familiar with some of the tutorials, you know, just having them

00:17:18.079 --> 00:17:22.880
do some hands-on labs. I think it's more beneficial than watching videos, reading textbooks. You're

00:17:22.880 --> 00:17:27.680
actually getting, you know, down and dirty with some of the code, and you're going to have errors

00:17:27.680 --> 00:17:32.719
along the way. That's the most important thing. I don't think anybody's not written a script that

00:17:32.719 --> 00:17:38.160
didn't function the first time. So having an understanding that there are going to be errors

00:17:38.160 --> 00:17:43.439
along the way, giving them the resources that they need, whether they're a visual learner.

00:17:43.439 --> 00:17:48.560
If they do prefer textbooks, that's okay. You know, some of the more stats oriented people, I would

